76561198051743158,Recommended,214970,11008492,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,jslotkin,"The Genre: Keyboard/mouse or twin-stick shooting physics platformer.The Awesome: Crazy over the top enemy wave and boss design. The first boss is an elaborate, punishing, multi-stage battle where you keep thinking it's dead and it just...keeps...coming! Then it finally dies and you think perhaps the next level will get off to a more relaxing start, and instead you find yourself careening downhill on a fragment of the boss you just killed, while ninjas lob increasingly dangerous explosives at you...and then there are some airstrikes...and then the airstrikes start to include missiles that turn into giant robot snakes. I still haven't gotten past the snakes, so I don't know what else that sequence might hold, but it inspired me to write a review.The Good: All the things you can do with the game's physics. Lots of movable/destroyable objects, vehicles, enemies with individually destroyable, independently moving sections.The Bad: The physics and controls feel very loose and floaty. Movement could be tighter and objects could feel like they have more weight and heft. Sometime you try to jump and it doesn't quite happen. It doesn't generally prevent you from being able to move around and do skillful things, but it is annoying.The Ugly: The game autosaves at checkpoints, and they are very far apart. There are more frequent checkpoints that you return to when you die, but if you actually quit the game, you may find yourself much further back. Some people may appreciate this feature, since it makes the game more challenging and perhaps increases playtime, while others may be annoyed by it.Verdict: The ideas in here are so cool...with a little bit of tolerance for the imperfect controls/physics you can have a lot of fun with it...especially if you can let your imagination fill in some of the gaps between the execution and the level of awesomeness that the game is aiming at (and mostly achieves)."
